EVT_8014227_DESC;The Doctors' plot in 1952/53 was the most dramatic anti-Jewish episode in the Soviet Union during Joseph Stalin's regime, involving the ""unmasking"" of a group of prominent Moscow doctors, predominantly Jews, as conspiratorial assassins of Soviet leaders. With the beginning of the Cold War, the State of Israel allying with the West, and Stalin's suspicions of any form of nationalism, the Soviet regime eliminated the Jewish Anti-Fascist Committee in 1948 and launched a campaign against so-called ""rootless cosmopolitans."" Also, in the course of his career, Stalin became increasingly suspicious towards physicians.

